              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Major suppliers</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Dematic, Intelligrated, Bastian, Hytrol</td>
                <td class="py-4">Dorner, Shuttleworth, mk North America</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ INDUSTRY 4.0 & IIoT ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="iiot-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Smart Conveyors</div>
        <h2 id="iiot-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Industry 4.0 &#x26; <span class="text-accent">IIoT</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Industry 4.0 extends conveyor automation beyond real-time control into data-driven optimization. IIoT (Industrial Internet of Things) sensors on conveyor components collect vibration, temperature, current, and runtime data. This data flows to cloud or edge platforms for analysis, visualization, and machine learning.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Predictive Maintenance</h3>
          <p>
            Vibration sensors on conveyor bearings, gearboxes, and motors detect early signs of wear. A bearing developing a fault produces a characteristic vibration signature months before failure. Predictive maintenance software (from vendors like SKF, Augury, and Nanoprecise) identifies these signatures and schedules replacement during planned downtime. The alternative , running to failure , causes unplanned conveyor shutdowns that stop entire packaging lines.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-4">OEE &#x26; Throughput Analytics</h3>
          <p>
            Automated conveyor systems generate data that feeds Overall Equipment Effectiveness (OEE) calculations. Product counters, speed sensors, and fault logs provide the availability, performance, and quality inputs OEE requires. Real-time OEE dashboards show line performance by shift, product, and conveyor section. Identifying the section with the lowest performance metric pinpoints the bottleneck for improvement.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Digital Twin &#x26; Simulation</h3>
          <p>
            A digital twin is a software model of the physical conveyor system. It runs the same PLC logic against simulated product flow. Engineers test new recipes, speed changes, and layout modifications in the digital twin before implementing them on the production floor. Siemens (Tecnomatik), Rockwell (Emulate), and Dematic offer digital twin platforms for conveyor system simulation.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Communication Protocols</h3>
          <p>
            Industry 4.0 conveyor systems use standard industrial protocols for device-to-PLC and PLC-to-cloud communication:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-ink">EtherNet/IP:</strong> Allen-Bradley standard. TCP/IP-based, widely supported by sensors and VFDs.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">PROFINET:</strong> Siemens standard. Ethernet-based, supports isochronous real-time (IRT) for high-speed motion.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">EtherCAT:</strong> Beckhoff-originated. Extremely fast cycle times (sub-millisecond) for servo-synchronized <a href="/conveyor-functions/indexing-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">indexing applications</a>.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">OPC UA:</strong> Vendor-neutral protocol for PLC-to-MES and PLC-to-cloud data exchange. Increasingly standard for Industry 4.0 interoperability.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">MQTT:</strong> Lightweight publish/subscribe protocol for IIoT sensor data. Used for edge-to-cloud communication in predictive maintenance systems.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ CONVEYOR TYPES FOR AUTOMATION ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="types-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Conveyor Types</div>
        <h2 id="types-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Conveyor Types in <span class="text-accent">Automated Systems</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Automated systems combine multiple conveyor types, each chosen for its function within the system:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-ink"><a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover">MDR Conveyors</a>:</strong> Built-in zone control makes MDR the most automation-ready conveyor type. Each zone operates independently with its own sensor and motor. Zero-pressure accumulation requires no PLC programming beyond zone configuration.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink"><a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover">Powered Roller Conveyors</a>:</strong> VFD-controlled powered roller sections handle continuous transport at adjustable speeds. Simpler controls than MDR but without zone-level accumulation.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink"><a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover">Accumulation Conveyors</a>:</strong> Zero-pressure accumulation absorbs rate differences between machines. Critical for maintaining line uptime when upstream and downstream machines run at different speeds or experience intermittent stops.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink"><a href="/conveyor-types/live-roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover">Live Roller Conveyors</a>:</strong> Belt-driven or chain-driven rollers provide continuous motion for transport sections between automated workstations.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink"><a href="/conveyor-functions/collating-laning/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover">Laning &#x26; Collating Conveyors</a>:</strong> Servo-controlled laning divides and groups product for automated case packing.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            For a complete overview of all conveyor types, visit the <a href="/conveyor-types/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor types directory</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ SELECTION CRITERIA ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="selection-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Planning</div>
        <h2 id="selection-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Planning an Automated <span class="text-accent">Conveyor System</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Successful conveyor automation projects start with clear requirements and avoid common over-specification traps:
          </p>
          <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Define automation level per section.</strong> Not every conveyor section needs PLC control. Transport sections between automated machines may need only a VFD-controlled motor. Accumulation zones need sensor-controlled logic. <a href="/conveyor-functions/reject-systems/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Reject zones</a> need tight integration with inspection devices. Match the automation level to the function.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Standardize the PLC platform.</strong> Mixing Allen-Bradley, Siemens, and Beckhoff on the same line creates maintenance headaches. Choose one platform and stick with it , even if a particular OEM machine ships with a different PLC brand. Insist on your standard or budget for controls conversion.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Plan for future expansion.</strong> Size the PLC with 20–30% spare I/O capacity. Run empty conduit to locations where future sensors or motors may install. Select a network architecture that supports additional nodes without rewiring.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Budget controls separately.</strong> Controls cost 15–40% of total automated conveyor system cost depending on automation level. Lumping controls into the conveyor hardware budget leads to under-specification. For detailed cost planning, see the <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor cost guide</a>.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Specify commissioning and training.</strong> Automated conveyor systems require on-site commissioning , PLC tuning, sensor calibration, VFD parameter setup, and integration testing with connected machines. Budget 2–4 weeks of commissioning time for a full packaging line. Include operator and maintenance training in the project scope.</li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

